,Recommended,269730,11253099,"Posted: 15 July, 2014",all,EURONAT3,"TLDR: If you enjoy all of golfs challenging aspects, this game will totally be worth it to you.As it says in the big blue box below, the game is an Early Access Game.  However, if you have a half decent computer, I highly recommend getting this game while it is still discounted for Early Access.There are a few things to consider:The NegativesGraphics settings are limited to your resolution and three quality settings: high, medium, and low.With graphics on low or medium, you only get a 5 yd x 5 yd putting grid when you get a 15 yd x 15 yd putting grid on high quality settings.The game is extremely GPU dependent.  My AMD FX-6350 is around 35% to 60% in the six cores while my GPU is almost always pinned on 99% or 100% at high graphics settings.UI feels clunky with mouse and keyboard but it is fine with a controller.The user created courses tend to get polluted with courses that really aren't that well made or aren't anywhere close to realistic.  However, if you look in the right places (the forums or other player created sites), you can find some very extraordinary courses.The PositivesOverall, the game is very realistic.  Of course there are a few bugs here and there due to the early access that cause some pretty strange ""physics,"" but that rarely ever happens.  Some examples:Ball below your feet = push right; vice versa for ball above your feet.The wind speeds seem very realistic when pushing the ball around along with the elevation changes.Putting takes some getting used to but it is solely based on the player controller ""marker"" that you move around to adjust your line and power.  Putting is basically the most polished aspect of the game IMO.The more difficult a shot is, the skinnier the ""perfect swing"" area will get.  Playing a draw, fade, high, or low shot all affect the margin of error when the player is swinging.The lie you have for your shot is a range of percentages.  Plugging into a bunker gives you ~40% to 60% of that clubs power for the shot out of the bunker and that percentage changes for each club.  Obviously a fairway wood is difficult to hit out of a fairway bunker.The course creator is very easy to use with a controller and has improved significantly since it first came out.Any specific questions, you are more than welcome to PM me or add me as a friend for some competition. :D"
