76561198110881362,Not Recommended,269730,16285097,"Posted: 9 June, 2015",all,ash,"[Update 21/10/2015]I upgraded my graphics card to an nVidia GTX 960 and the game now runs at an acceptable level of smoothness (in full screen).However for any other potential buyers, be aware that The Golf Club runs very poorly on my ATI HD5770 1GB card (5 years old).  The HD5770  continued to work very well (with sensible settings) in every game I tried, except for The Golf Club (see below).   I upgraded simply because I needeed a card that supports GPU rendering in Blender.  At least I have not completely wasted my money now on this game.[End Update]This game has a number of problems:Inexplicably it's only playable on my HD5700, 8GB, AMD 3.3Ghz dual core desktop PC in windowed mode.  In fullscreen mode constant stuttering destroys any ability to time shots properly.  Reducing all graphics settings made no difference, only windowed  mode reduced the stuttering to playable levels.  Even then, the game feels sluggish, trees pop into view during the tracking camera views and even sound effects seem to cause stutters.I have found it almost impossible to reliably play a shots with say 75% or 80% power.  There is no visual indicator of your shot power, you just have to watch the backswing and start the fore swing when you feel the time is right.  As a result I have to just check the current distance to hole / wind and then pick the club with a 100% power distance that matches the required distance.  This makes lobs and green approach shots extremely difficult frustrating.  (It's essential to play with a controller with analog sticks, I have a logitech dual action).The course designer has very poor usability.  I've tried to landscape a links course from scratch (no holes, trees) by sculpting terrain.  The raise terrain tool is the most ridiculous tool I've seen in any design program.You change the raise/lower height by holding shift and scrolling the mouse wheel.  However the larger the brush the larger the height change. For example if I have a very large brush (for large scale terrain editing), the height jumps to 0 to 800 feet! The only way to get smaller height change is to shrink the brush to the smallest size, then adjust the height in small increments, then increase the brush size again and apply the change.  To top it all off, once you apply the brush, the height settings are lost and you have to go through the same stupid process.  Imaging doing this to sculpt an entire map.The tree shadows, even at high quality are quite blocky and unrealistic.  More importantly when there are shadows on the green it makes seeing the hole and judging the borrow very dififcult.  Maybe this is how it is on a real course but in real life there is no grid overlaying the green that is obscured by shadows.The developer provides no manual or useful playing guide.  There are video tutorials that explain some of the basics but but they are brief / out of date.I wanted to like this game as there are so few new golf games these days.  However this is a released game, not early access and as such it is simply not good enough in it's current state.  There were more enjoyable golf games available 12 years ago.If at least the performance issues and the swing power issue were fixed I'd certainly like the game a lot more and would likely revise this review."
