,Not Recommended,269730,11006308,"Posted: 1 July, 2014",all,ToastyPotato,"Preliminary feelings as of June 2014:This game seems to try very hard to overheat my video card.  I've run Titanfall, Arkham Origins, and Battlefield on very high settings without any issue, but this game slowly degrades and starts glitching out and artifacting all over the place.  The temps are higher than those other games.  I'm running a Radeon r9 270.The swing/put mechanism is nice I guess, but it is certainly not inherently better than the more classic interfaces from older games.  One could argue that this introduces a realistic element of ""skill"" and ""practice"" but that would be neglecting to mention that not everyone has the same controller setup, nor do people have the same hands, nor do people have the same amount of time to practice.  This is a video game that people paid for so there really isn't a need to create a gap to simulate the fact that some people are just going to be bad at golf without massive amounts of practice.  At the very least, add in a more classical control scheme option for more casual players so that people who want a fun PC golf game can have it while the more hardcore golf fans can have their some what more sim styled game at the same time.The courses are plentiful and you can edit and create new ones so there really is no point in rating those.  The course system they have is excellent, however and exactly what a golf game needs.  Kudos to that.  Another kudos is the way you play against ghost rivals.Minor annoyance:  Cannot name guest players in hot seat multiplayer.  Jeopardy on the NES lets me name each player.  No excuses.Unfortunately I cannot recommend the game for the current price at this moment.  I'll fiddle with the game a bit more to see if I can improve the performance, and hopefully future patches improve everything in general.  This has the makings of the best golf game on for PCs, and one of the best ever, but it definitely has a ways to go."
